    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-06-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-06-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="674"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d674">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.51 Chase National Bank/7</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Chase National Bank</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-06-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 20, 1928</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sirs</hi>: With reference to letters of Messrs. Rushmore,
                    Bisbee and Stern<note n="22" xml:id="d674fn22">Legal firm, New York.</note>
                    addressed to the Department under dates of May 22 and June 14, 1928,<note n="23"
                        xml:id="d674fn23">Neither printed.</note> regarding your interest in
                    negotiating a credit arrangement with the Cuban Government, I beg to inform you
                    that, in the light of the information at hand, the Department desires to offer
                        <pb facs="0771" n="653" xml:id="pg_653"/> no objection to this proposed
                    financing on the terms and conditions set forth in the Supplemental Agreement
                    enclosed with the above-mentioned letter of June 14.</p>
                <p>You of course appreciate that, as pointed out in the Department’s announcement of
                    March 3, 1922,<note n="24" xml:id="d674fn24">
                        <ref target="frus1922v01#pg_557">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1922, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 557</ref>.</note> the Department of
                    State does not pass upon the merits of foreign loans as business propositions
                    nor assume any responsibility in connection with such transactions, also that no
                    reference to the attitude of this Government should be made in any prospectus or
                    otherwise.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis White</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Assistant Secretary</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
